{{About|Adolf Hitler's dog|similar names and related words|Blondie (disambiguation){{!}}Blondie}} {{Use dmy dates|date=April 2016}} {{Infobox animal | name = Blondi | image = Bundesarchiv B 145 Bild-F051673-0059, Adolf Hitler und Blondi auf dem Berghof.jpg | caption = [[Adolf Hitler]] holding Blondi on a leash. | species = ''[[Canis lupus familiaris]]'' | breed = [[German Shepherd]] | gender = Female | nationality = [[Germany]] | birth_date = 1941 | death_date = {{Death date|1945|04|29|df=y}} | owner = [[Adolf Hitler]] | children = Wulf and four other pups }}
'''Blondi''' (1941 – 29 April 1945){{efn|Some sources incorrectly suggest 1934 as Blondi's date of birth.<ref>{{Cite book | author=Eatwell, Roger | title=Fascism: A History | year=1995 | publisher=Chatto & Windus | location= | isbn= | page=152}}</ref>}}<ref>Kershaw, Ian. ''Hitler: A Biography'', W.W. Norton & Co. p. 252. {{ISBN|0-393-06757-2}}</ref> was [[Adolf Hitler]]'s [[German Shepherd]], a gift as a puppy<ref>{{Cite book | last=Comfort | first=David | title=The First Pet History of the World | year=1994 | publisher=Simon & Schuster | location=New York | isbn=0-671-89102-2 | page=247}}</ref><ref>some sources suggest the Summer of 1942 (see: {{Cite book | author=Wires, Richard | title=Terminology of the Third Reich | year=1985 | publisher=Ball State University | location= | isbn= | pages=9}}) or even February 1943 (see: [http://timelines.ws/countries/GERM1939_1944.HTML timelines.ws] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091114074358/http://timelines.ws/countries/GERM1939_1944.HTML |date=14 November 2009 }})</ref> from [[Martin Bormann]] in 1941. Blondi stayed with Hitler even after his move into the ''[[Führerbunker]]'' located underneath the garden of the [[Reich Chancellery]] on 16 January 1945.<ref>{{cite book |last=Beevor |first=Antony | authorlink=Antony Beevor |title=Berlin: The Downfall 1945|publisher=Viking-Penguin Books|year=2002|isbn=978-0-670-03041-5|page=139}}</ref>
Hitler was reportedly very fond of Blondi, keeping her by his side and allowing her to sleep in his bed in the bunker. According to Hitler's secretary [[Traudl Junge]], this affection was not shared by [[Eva Braun]], Hitler's companion, who preferred her two [[Scottish Terrier]] dogs named Negus and Stasi.
Blondi played a role in Nazi propaganda by portraying Hitler as an animal lover. Dogs like Blondi were coveted as "{{lang|de|germanische Urhunde}}", being close to the wolf, and became very fashionable during the Nazi era.<ref>Sax, Boria (2000). ''Animals in the Third Reich: Pets, Scapegoats, and the Holocaust''. Foreword by Klaus P. Fischer. New York and London: Continuum. {{ISBN|978-0-8264-1289-8}}.</ref> On 29 April 1945, Hitler expressed doubts about the cyanide capsules he had received through [[Heinrich Himmler]]'s SS.<ref>Kershaw, Ian (2008). ''Hitler: A Biography'', W.W. Norton & Co. pp. 951–952.</ref> To verify the capsules' potency, Hitler ordered Dr. [[Werner Haase]] to test one on Blondi, who died as a result.<ref>Kershaw, Ian. ''Hitler: A Biography'', W.W. Norton & Co. p. 952.</ref>
==Blondi's puppies== In March<ref>{{Cite book |author1=Galante, Pierre |author2=Silianoff, Eugène |author3=Silianoff, Eugene | title=Voices from the Bunker | year=1989 | publisher=G.P. Putnam's | location=New York, NY | isbn=0-399-13404-2 | page=12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book |author1=Dekkers, Midas |author2=Vincent, Paul | title=Dearest Pet: On Bestiality | year=2000 | publisher=Verso | location= | isbn=1-85984-310-7 | page=171}}</ref> or in early April<ref>Eberle, Henrik and Uhl, Matthias, ed. (2005). ''The Hitler Book: The Secret Dossier Prepared for Stalin'', New York: PublicAffairs, p. 188. {{ISBN|1-58648-366-8}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book | last=Brush | first=Karen A. | title=Everything Your Dog Expects You to Know | year=2007 | publisher=New Holland Publishers Ltd | location= | isbn=1-84537-954-3 | page=108}}</ref> (likely 4 April)<ref name="Abbyk">{{cite web |url=http://abbyk9.blogspot.com/2006/03/distant-relatives.htm |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071109134756/http://abbyk9.blogspot.com/2006/03/distant-relatives.htm |archivedate=9 November 2007 |title=Distant Relatives |publisher=Abby K-9 |date=March 2006}}</ref> 1945, she had a litter of five puppies with [[Gerdy Troost]]'s German Shepherd, Harras. Hitler named one of the puppies "Wulf", his favorite nickname and the meaning of his own first name, [[Adolf]] ("noble wolf"),<ref>Bullock, Alan (1962). ''Adolf Hitler: A Study in Tyranny'', Penguin Books, p. 785.</ref> and he began to train her.<ref>{{Cite book |author1=Kohler, Joachim |author2=Taylor, Ronald K. | title=Wagner's Hitler: The Prophet and His Disciple | year=2001 | publisher=Polity Press | location= | isbn=0-7456-2710-2 | page=19}}</ref> One of Blondi's puppies was reserved for [[Eva Braun]]'s sister [[Gretl Braun|Gretl]]. Eva sent Gretl a letter containing a photo of Blondi and three of her puppies, Gretl's being indicated with an arrow.<ref>{{Cite book | author=Gun, Nerin E. | title=Eva Braun: Hitler's Mistress | year=1969 | publisher=Meredith Press | location= | isbn=0-7456-2710-2 | pages=241, 246}}</ref>
==Other dogs== During his military service in [[World War I]], Hitler rescued a stray white [[Fox Terrier]] named "Fuchsl". Hitler had great affection for the dog, and, when he was not on duty at the front, he would spend much of his free time playing with the dog in the barracks. Hitler was profoundly distraught when he lost him.<ref name=Hubris>{{cite book | last =Kershaw | first =Ian | authorlink =Ian Kershaw | year=1998 | isbn=0-393-320359 | title=Hitler 1889-1936: Hubris | publisher=Penguin Press}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book |author1=Giblin, James |author2=Payne, Robert | title=The Life and Death of Adolf Hitler | year=2000 | publisher=New York, Praeger [1973] | location= | isbn=0-395-90371-8 | page=20}}</ref>
He had been given a German Shepherd before named "Prinz" in 1921, during his years of poverty, but he had been forced to lodge the dog elsewhere. However, she managed to escape and return to him. Hitler, who adored the loyalty and obedience of the dog, thereafter developed a great liking for the breed.<ref>{{cite book |last=Beevor |first=Antony |title=Berlin: The Downfall 1945|publisher=Viking-Penguin Books|year=2002|isbn=978-0-670-03041-5 |page=357}}</ref>
He also owned a German Shepherd called "Muckl".<ref>{{Cite book | author=von Schirach, Baldur | authorlink=Baldur von Schirach | title=Ich glaubte an Hitler | year=1967 | publisher=Mosaik Verlag | location= | isbn= | page=106}}</ref> Before Blondi, Hitler had two German Shepherd dogs, a mother [born 1926] and daughter [born ca. 1930] – both named Blonda. In some photos taken during the 1930s the younger Blonda is incorrectly labeled as Blondi<ref name="Abbyk"/> (in most cases photograph descriptions were written later).
In May 1942, Hitler bought another young German Shepherd "from a minor official in the post office in [[Ingolstadt]]"<ref>Goebbels' Diary, 30 May 1942: "'' He [Hitler] has bought himself a young German Shepherd dog called "Blondi" which is the apple of his eye. It was touching listening to him say that he enjoyed walking with this dog so much, because only with it could he be sure that [his companion] would not start talking about the war or politics. One notices time and time again that the Führer is slowly but surely becoming lonely. It is very touching to see him play with this young German Shepherd dog. The animal has grown so accustomed to him that it will hardly take a step without him. It is very nice to watch the Führer with his dog. At the moment the dog is the only living thing that is constantly with him. At night it sleeps at the foot of his bed, it is allowed into his sleeping compartment in the special train and enjoys a number of privileges...that no human would ever dare to claim. He bought the dog from a minor official in the post office in Ingolstadt.''"</ref> to keep Blondi company. He called her Bella.<ref>{{Cite book | last=Irving | first=David John Cawdell | authorlink=David John Cawdell Irving | title=Hitler's war | year=1977 | publisher=Viking Press | location=New York | isbn=0-670-37412-1 | page=328}}</ref> According to [[Traudl Junge]], Eva Braun was very fond of her two [[Scottish Terrier]] dogs named Negus and Stasi. She usually kept them away from Blondi.<ref>{{cite book | last = Junge | first = Traudl | authorlink = Traudl Junge | year = 2003 | title = [[Until the Final Hour|Until the Final Hour: Hitler's Last Secretary]] | publisher = [[Weidenfeld & Nicolson]] | location = London | isbn = 978-0-297-84720-5 | page = 77}}</ref>
==Death of Blondi and other dogs== During the course of 29 April 1945, Hitler learned of the death of his ally [[Benito Mussolini]] at the hands of [[Italian partisans]]. This, along with the fact the Soviet Red Army was closing in on his location, strengthened Hitler in his resolve not to allow himself or his wife to be captured. That afternoon, Hitler expressed doubts about the cyanide capsules he had received through [[Heinrich Himmler]]'s [[Schutzstaffel|SS]].<ref>Kershaw, Ian (2008). ''Hitler: A Biography'', W.W. Norton & Co. pp. 951–953. {{ISBN|0-393-06757-2}}</ref> By this point, Hitler regarded Himmler as a traitor. To verify the capsules' contents, Hitler—who already intended to have Blondi killed so that she did not fall into the hands of the Russians<ref>Gitta Sereny, Albert Speer: His Battle with the Truth, p. 528</ref>—ordered Dr. [[Werner Haase]] to test one on Blondi, and the dog died as a result.<ref>Kershaw, Ian (2008). ''Hitler: A Biography'', W.W. Norton & Co. p. 952. {{ISBN|0-393-06757-2}}</ref> Hitler became completely inconsolable.<ref>{{Cite book | last=O'Donnell | first=James | authorlink=James P. O'Donnell | title=The Bunker: The History of the Reich Chancellery Group | year=1978 | publisher=Houghton Mifflin | location=Boston | isbn=0-395-25719-0 | page=166}}</ref>
According to a report commissioned by [[Joseph Stalin]] and based on eyewitness accounts, Hitler's dog-handler ''[[Feldwebel]]'' [[Fritz Tornow]] took Blondi's pups and shot them in the garden of the bunker complex on 30 April, after Hitler and Eva Braun committed suicide. He also killed Eva Braun's two dogs, Frau [[Gerda Christian]]'s dogs, and his own [[dachshund]]. Tornow was later captured by the Allies.<ref>Eberle, Henrik and Uhl, Matthias, ed. (2005). ''The Hitler Book: The Secret Dossier Prepared for Stalin'', New York: PublicAffairs, p. 273. {{ISBN|1-58648-366-8}}</ref> Hitler's nurse, [[Erna Flegel]], said in 2005 that Blondi's death had affected the people in the bunker more than Eva Braun's suicide.<ref>Harding, Luke. [https://www.theguardian.com/world/2005/may/02/artsandhumanities.secondworldwar "Hitler's nurse breaks 60 years of silence"], ''The Guardian'', May 2, 2005.</ref> After the [[battle in Berlin]] ended, the remains of Hitler, Braun, and two dogs (thought to be Blondi and her offspring Wulf) were discovered in a shell crater by a unit of [[SMERSH]], the Soviet counter-intelligence agency.<ref>{{cite book |last=Beevor |first=Antony |title=Berlin: The Downfall 1945|publisher=Viking-Penguin Books|year=2002|isbn=978-0670030415|page=399}}</ref><ref>According to the autopsy, both dogs were shot and Blondi was killed by poison. Some sources say that Wolf was killed with the other puppies in the Chancellery garden (see {{Cite book | last=Moorhouse | first=Roger | authorlink=Roger Moorhouse | title=Killing Hitler: The Plots, The Assassins, and the Dictator Who Cheated Death | year=2007 | publisher=Bantam | location= | isbn=0-553-38255-1 | page=323}}).</ref> The dog thought to be Blondi was exhumed and photographed by the Soviets.<ref>Le Tissier, Tony (1992). ''Berlin Then and Now'', After the Battle.</ref>
