{{about|the footballer|the actor|Jim Bartley (actor)}}
{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2016}}
{{Use British English|date=June 2016}}
'''James William Edward Bartley''' (baptised 28 May 1902<ref>''England, Select Births and Christenings, 1538-1975''</ref> – 21 September 1939) was an English professional [[association football|football]]er of the 1920s.<ref name="obituary">{{cite news |title=Mr. J. W. E. Bartley |url=https://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0001454/19390929/093/0004 |accessdate=19 June 2018 |work=Chatham News |date=29 September 1939 |page=4 |quote=Much regret will be felt, particularly among football followers locally at the death of Mr. James William Edward Bartley....}}</ref>

Bartley was born in [[Coseley]], [[Staffordshire]],<ref>''1911 England Census''</ref> the son of George and Eliza Bartley. In 1916, during the First World War, his father died in [[Mesopotamia]] of wounds received while serving with the [[North Staffordshire (Prince of Wales's) Regiment]].<ref name="obituary"/><ref>''UK, Soldiers Died in the Great War, 1914-1919''</ref> Bartley joined [[Gillingham F.C.|Gillingham]] from [[Bilston Town F.C.|Bilston United]] in 1926. He made his debut for the club in September of the same year against [[Aberdare Athletic F.C.|Aberdare Athletic]] and played in the next three matches, but was then out of the team for six months.  He returned to the team in April 1927 against [[Exeter City F.C.|Exeter City]] and played five more times that season,<ref>{{cite book  | last =  Brown  | first = Tony|title = The Definitive Gillingham F.C.: A Complete Record  | publisher = Soccerdata  | year = 2003  | isbn = 1-899468-20-X   | page =40}}</ref>  but played only once in 1927–28 and twice in 1928–29.<ref>{{cite book  | last =  Brown  | first = Tony|title = The Definitive Gillingham F.C.: A Complete Record  | publisher = Soccerdata  | year = 2003  | isbn = 1-899468-20-X   | page =41}}</ref><ref>{{cite book  | last =  Brown  | first = Tony|title = The Definitive Gillingham F.C.: A Complete Record  | publisher = Soccerdata  | year = 2003  | isbn = 1-899468-20-X   | page =4q}}</ref>

Bartley had a further run of eight games in the Gillingham team in September and October 1929, but after two further games later that season,<ref>{{cite book  | last =  Brown  | first = Tony|title = The Definitive Gillingham F.C.: A Complete Record  | publisher = Soccerdata  | year = 2003  | isbn = 1-899468-20-X   | page =43}}</ref> he left to join Canterbury Waverley.<ref name="triggs40">{{cite book |first=Roger|last= Triggs|title=The Men Who Made Gillingham Football Club|publisher=Tempus Publishing Ltd |year=2001|isbn=0-7524-2243-X|page=10}}</ref>

Bartley later ran a pub, the Good Intent, in Gillingham. In September 1939, "after a period of indifferent health", he died unexpectedly at age 37, the same age his father died. He was survived by a widow and two children.<ref name="obituary"/>

