[[File:The Jack Pine, by Tom Thomson.jpg|thumb|upright=1.2|''[[The Jack Pine]]'', Winter 1916–17. 127.9 × 139.8 cm. [[National Gallery of Canada]], [[Ottawa]]]]
[[File:Tom Thomson - Black Spruce and Maple - Google Art Project.jpg|thumb|upright=1.2|''Black Spruce and Maple'', Fall 1915. Sketch.{{efn|group=note|"[[Oil sketch|Sketch]]" indicates that the work is a smaller [[Oil paint|oil]] work, generally on [[Panel painting|wood panel]]. The dimensions are often close to 21.6 × 26.7 cm (8½ x 10½ in.) but sometimes as small as 12.8 x 18.2 cm (5<small>{{frac|1|16}}</small> x 7<small>{{frac|3|16}}</small> in.).}} [[Art Gallery of Ontario]], [[Toronto]]]]

'''Thomas John Thomson''' (August 5, 1877{{spaced ndash}}July 8, 1917) was a Canadian artist active in the early 20th century. During his short career he produced roughly 400 [[oil sketch]]s on small [[Panel painting|wood panels]] along with around 50 larger works on canvas. His works consist almost entirely of landscapes, depicting trees, skies, lakes, and rivers. His paintings use broad brush strokes and a liberal application of paint to capture the  beauty and colour of the [[Ontario]] landscape. Thomson's accidental death at 39 by drowning came just after the founding of the [[Group of Seven (artists)|Group of Seven]] and is seen as a tragedy for [[Canadian art]].

Raised in rural Ontario, Thomson was born into a large family of farmers and displayed no immediate artistic talent. He worked several jobs before attending a business college, eventually developing skills in [[penmanship]] and [[Copperplate script|copperplate]] writing. At the turn of the 20th century, he was employed in [[Seattle]] and [[Toronto]] as a pen artist at several different [[photoengraving]] firms, including [[Grip Ltd.]] There he met those who eventually formed the Group of Seven, including [[J. E. H. MacDonald]], [[Lawren Harris]], [[Frederick Varley]], [[Franklin Carmichael]] and [[Arthur Lismer]]. In May 1912, he visited [[Algonquin Provincial Park|Algonquin Park]]—a major public park and forest reservation in [[Central Ontario]]—for the first time. It was there that he acquired his first sketching equipment and, following MacDonald's advice, began to capture nature scenes. He became enraptured with the area and repeatedly returned, typically spending his winters in Toronto and the rest of the year in the Park. While his earliest paintings were not outstanding technically, they showed a good grasp of [[Composition (visual arts)|composition]] and colour handling. His later paintings vary in composition and contain vivid colours and thickly applied paint. His later work has had a great influence on Canadian art—paintings such as ''[[The Jack Pine]]'' and ''[[The West Wind (painting)|The West Wind]]'' have taken a prominent place in the [[culture of Canada]] and are some of the country's most iconic works.

Thomson developed a reputation during his lifetime as a veritable [[Outdoor enthusiast|outdoorsman]], talented in both fishing and [[canoeing]], although his talents in the latter have been contested. The circumstances of his drowning on [[Canoe Lake (Nipissing District)|Canoe Lake]] in Algonquin Park, linked with his image as a master canoeist, led to unsubstantiated but persistent rumours that he had been murdered or committed suicide.

Although he died before the formal establishment of the Group of Seven, Thomson is often considered an unofficial member. His art is typically exhibited with the rest of the Group's, nearly all of which remains in Canada—mainly at the [[Art Gallery of Ontario]] in Toronto, the [[National Gallery of Canada]] in [[Ottawa]], the [[McMichael Canadian Art Collection]] in [[Kleinburg]] and the Tom Thomson Art Gallery in [[Owen Sound]].

==Life==
===Early years===

Thomas John "Tom" Thomson was born in [[Claremont, Ontario]], the sixth of John and Margaret Thomson's ten children.{{sfnb|Silcox|2015|p=[https://www.aci-iac.ca/art-books/tom-thomson/biography/#boyhood-years 4]}} He was raised in [[Leith, Ontario]], near [[Owen Sound]], in the municipality of [[Meaford, Ontario|Meaford]].{{sfnb|Silcox|Town|2017|p=41}} Thomson and his siblings enjoyed both drawing and painting, although he did not immediately display any major talents.{{sfnb|Silcox|2015|p=[https://www.aci-iac.ca/art-books/tom-thomson/biography/#boyhood-years 4]}} He was eventually taken out of school for a year because of ill health, including a respiratory problem variously described as "weak lungs" or "inflammatory [[rheumatism]]".{{sfnb|Silcox|Town|2017|p=41}}<ref>{{harvp|MacDonald|1917|p=47}} quoted in {{harvp|Hill|2002|p=113}}</ref> This gave him free time to explore the woods near his home and develop an appreciation of nature.{{sfnb|Silcox|2015|p=[https://www.aci-iac.ca/art-books/tom-thomson/biography/#boyhood-years 4]}}

The family were unsuccessful as farmers; both Thomson and his father often abandoned their chores to go hiking, hunting and fishing.{{sfnb|Murray|1998|pp=14–15, 22–25}} Thomson regularly went on walks with Dr. William Brodie (1831–1909), his grandmother's first cousin.{{sfnb|Silcox|2015|p=[https://www.aci-iac.ca/art-books/tom-thomson/significance-and-critical-issues/#the-artist-and-nature 57]}}{{sfnb|Murray|1999|p=5}} Brodie was a well-known [[Entomology|entomologist]], [[Ornithology|ornithologist]] and [[Botany|botanist]], and Thomson's sister Margaret later recounted that they collected specimens on long walks together.{{sfnb|Murray|1999|pp=6–7}}{{sfnb|Wadland|2002|p=93}}

Thomson was also enthusiastic about sports, once breaking his toe while playing football.{{sfnb|Silcox|Town|2017|p=41}} He was an excellent swimmer and fisherman, inheriting his passion for the latter from his grandfather and father.{{sfnb|Hill|2002|p=113}} Like most of those in his community, he regularly attended church. Some stories say that he sketched in the hymn books during services and entertained his sisters with caricatures of their neighbours. His sisters later said that they had fun "guessing who they were", indicating that he was not necessarily adept at capturing people's likeness.{{sfnb|Silcox|Town|2017|p=41}}

[[File:Young Tom Thomson.jpg|thumb|left|Portrait of a young Tom Thomson, {{circa|lk=no|1900}}]]

Each of Thomson's nine siblings received an inheritance from their paternal grandfather.{{sfnb|Hill|2002|p=113}} Thomson received $2000 in 1898 but seems to have spent it quickly.{{sfnb|Silcox|Town|2017|p=42}} A year later, he entered a machine shop apprenticeship at an iron foundry owned by William Kennedy, a close friend of his father, but left only eight months later.{{sfnb|Hill|2002|p=113}}{{sfnb|Silcox|2015|p=[https://www.aci-iac.ca/art-books/tom-thomson/biography/#early-adult-years 6]}} Also in 1899, he volunteered to fight in the [[Second Boer War]], but was turned down because of a medical condition.{{sfnb|Silcox|2006|pp=107–08}} He tried to enlist for the Boer War three times in all, but was denied each time.{{sfnb|Silcox|Town|2017|p=41}}

In 1901, Thomson enrolled at Canada Business College in [[Chatham–Kent|Chatham, Ontario]]. The school advertised instruction in [[shorthand|stenography]], [[bookkeeping]], [[business correspondence]] and "plain and ornamental [[penmanship]]".{{sfnb|Hill|2002|p=113}} There, he developed abilities in penmanship and [[copperplate script|copperplate]]—necessary skills for a clerk.{{sfnb|Stacey|2002|p=50}} After graduating at the end of 1901, he travelled briefly to [[Winnipeg]] before leaving for [[Seattle]] in January 1902, joining his older brother, George Thomson.{{sfnb|Hill|2002|p=113}}{{sfnb|Stacey|2002|p=50}}{{sfnb|Silcox|Town|2017|p=42}} George and cousin F. R. McLaren had established the Acme Business School in Seattle, listed as the 11th largest business school in the United States.{{sfnb|Hill|2002|p=113}}{{sfnb|Murray|1971|p=9}} Thomson worked briefly as an elevator operator at [[The Diller Hotel]]. By 1902, two more of his brothers, Ralph and Henry, had moved west to join the family's new school.{{sfnb|Silcox|2015|p=[https://www.aci-iac.ca/art-books/tom-thomson/biography/#early-adult-years 6]}}

===Graphic design work===
====Seattle (1901–04)====
After studying at the business school for six months, Thomson was hired at Maring & Ladd as a pen artist, [[Drafter|draftsman]] and [[Etching|etcher]].{{sfnb|Hill|2002|p=113}}{{sfnb|Stacey|2002|p=50}}{{sfnb|Silcox|2015|p=[https://www.aci-iac.ca/art-books/tom-thomson/biography/#early-adult-years 7]}} He mainly produced business cards, brochures and posters, as well as [[CMYK color model|three-colour printing]].{{sfnb|Stacey|2002|p=50}}{{sfnb|Silcox|2015|p=[https://www.aci-iac.ca/art-books/tom-thomson/biography/#early-adult-years 7]}} Having previously learned [[calligraphy]], he specialized in lettering, drawing and painting.{{sfnb|Silcox|2015|p=[https://www.aci-iac.ca/art-books/tom-thomson/biography/#early-adult-years 7]}} While working at Maring & Ladd, he was known to be stubborn; his brother Fraser wrote that, instead of completing his work according to the direction provided, he would use his own design ideas, which angered his boss.{{sfnb|Stacey|2002|pp=50–51}} Thomson may have also worked as a [[Freelancer|freelance]] commercial designer, but there are no extant examples of such work.{{sfnb|Stacey|2002|p=51}}

He eventually moved on to a local engraving company. Despite a good salary he left by the end of 1904. He quickly returned to Leith, possibly prompted by a rejected marriage proposal after his brief summer romance with [[Alice Elinor Lambert]].{{sfnb|Stacey|2002|p=52}}{{sfnb|Silcox|2015|p=[https://www.aci-iac.ca/art-books/tom-thomson/biography/#early-adult-years 7]}} Lambert, who never married, later became a writer;{{sfnb|Silcox|Town|2017|p=43}} in one of her stories, she describes a young girl who refuses an artist's proposal and later regrets her decision.{{sfnb|Silcox|2015|p=[https://www.aci-iac.ca/art-books/tom-thomson/biography/#early-adult-years 7]}}

====Toronto (1905–12)====
{{See also|Grip Ltd.}}

[[File:Profile of the painter Tom Thomson wearing a hat.jpg|thumb|Profile of Thomson wearing a suit and hat, {{circa|lk=no|1905–10}}. During this time, Thomson was known to dress well and spend his money on nice clothes and fine dining.]]

Thomson moved to Toronto in the summer of 1905.{{sfnb|Wadland|2002|p=92}} His first job upon his return to Canada was at the photo-engraving firm Legg Brothers, earning $11 a week.{{sfnb|Stacey|2002|p=52}}{{sfnb|Silcox|2015|p=[https://www.aci-iac.ca/art-books/tom-thomson/biography/#graphic-design-in-toronto 7]}} He spent his free time reading poetry and going to concerts, the theatre and sporting events.{{sfnb|Silcox|2006|p=127}} In a letter to an aunt, he wrote, "I love poetry best."{{sfnb|Murray|1999|p=viii}} Friends described him during this time as "periodically erratic and sensitive, with fits of unreasonable despondency". Apart from buying art supplies, he spent his money on expensive clothes, fine dining and tobacco.{{sfnb|Silcox|2015|p=[https://www.aci-iac.ca/art-books/tom-thomson/biography/#graphic-design-in-toronto 7]}} Around this time, he may have studied briefly with [[William Cruikshank (painter)|William Cruikshank]], a British artist who taught at the [[OCAD University|Ontario College of Art]].<ref name="Cruikshank"/> Cruikshank was likely Thomson's only art instructor.{{sfnb|Silcox|2015|p=[https://www.aci-iac.ca/art-books/tom-thomson/biography/#graphic-design-in-toronto 9]}}

In 1908 or 1909, Thomson joined [[Grip Ltd.]], a firm in Toronto that specialized in design and lettering work.{{efn|group=note|Sources disagree on the timing of Thomson's hiring. Grip supervisor Albert H. Robson wrote in 1932 that he was hired in 1907,<ref>{{harvp|Robson|1932|p=138}} quoted in {{harvp|Hill|2002|p=113n16}}</ref> but by 1937 Robson was instead writing that he was hired in 1908.<ref>{{harvp|Robson|1937|p=5}} quoted in {{harvp|Hill|2002|p=113n16}}</ref> Robert Stacey has suggested December 1908;{{sfnb|Stacey|2002|p=50}} David Silcox the beginning of 1909;{{sfnb|Silcox|2015|p=[https://www.aci-iac.ca/art-books/tom-thomson/biography/#graphic-design-in-toronto 9]}} and [[Joan Murray (art historian)|Joan Murray]] December 1908 or January 1909.{{sfnb|Murray|2002b|p=310}} Curator Charles Hill noted that Thomson is listed in the ''Toronto City Directory'' between 1906 and 1909 as working with Legg Bros. Photo Engravers; in 1910 merely as an artist living at 99 Gerrard E.; and in 1911 as at Grip Ltd. Hill supposes that Thomson therefore likely began at Grip in late 1909, after the information for the 1910 directory was collected.{{sfnb|Hill|2002|p=113n16}}}} Grip was the leading graphic-design company in the country and introduced [[Art Nouveau]], [[Steel engraving|metal engraving]] and the [[CMYK color model|four-colour process]] to Canada.{{sfnb|King|2010|p=14}} Albert Robson, then the art director at Grip, recalled that Thomson's early work at the firm was mostly in lettering and decorative designs for booklets and labels.<ref>{{harvp|Robson|1932|p=138}} quoted in {{harvp|Stacey|2002|p=53}}</ref> He wrote that Thomson made friends slowly but eventually found similar interests to his coworkers.<ref>{{harvp|Robson|1937|p=6}} quoted in {{harvp|Hill|2002|p=114}}</ref> Several of the employees at Grip had been members of the Toronto Art Students' League, a group of newspaper artists, illustrators and commercial artists active between 1886 and 1904.{{sfnb|Hill|2002|p=115}} The members sketched in parts of [[eastern Canada]] and published an annual calendar with illustrations depicting Canadian history and rural life.{{sfnb|Stacey|1998|p=96n9}}

The senior artist at Grip, [[J. E. H. MacDonald]], encouraged his staff to paint outside in their spare time to better hone their skills.{{sfnb|Stacey|2002|p=58}} It was at Grip that many of the eventual members of the [[Group of Seven (artists)|Group of Seven]] would meet. In December 1910, artist William Smithson Broadhead was hired, joined by [[Arthur Lismer]] in February 1911.{{sfnb|Hill|2002|p=114}} Robson eventually hired [[Frederick Varley]], followed by [[Franklin Carmichael]] in April 1911.{{sfnb|Murray|2002b|p=310}}{{sfnb|Murray|2004|p=16}} Although Thomson was not himself a member,{{sfnb|Hill|2002|p=117}}{{sfnb|Silcox|2015|p=[https://www.aci-iac.ca/art-books/tom-thomson/biography/#graphic-design-in-toronto 9n2]}} it was at the [[The Arts and Letters Club of Toronto|Arts and Letters Club]] that MacDonald introduced Thomson to [[Lawren Harris]].{{sfnb|Murray|2004|p=16}} The club was considered the "centre of living culture in Toronto", providing an informal environment for the artistic community.{{sfnb|Reid|1970|p=28}} Every member of what would become the original Group of Seven had now met.{{sfnb|Silcox|2015|p=[https://www.aci-iac.ca/art-books/tom-thomson/biography/#graphic-design-in-toronto 9]}} MacDonald left Grip in November 1911 to do freelance work and spend more time painting,{{sfnb|Stacey|Bishop|1996|p=118}} after the Ontario government purchased his canvas ''By the River (Early Spring)'' (1911).{{sfnb|Hill|2002|p=114}}

