===Painting career===
====Exploring Algonquin Park (1912–13)====
{{See also|Drowned Land|Algonquin Provincial Park|James MacCallum}}

[[Image:Tom Thomson.jpg|thumb|Thomson fishing in [[Algonquin Park]], {{circa|lk=no}} 1914–16. He was enamoured with the Park and many of his works were painted in the area.]]

[[Algonquin Provincial Park|Algonquin Park]] was established in 1893 by [[Oliver Mowat]] and the [[Legislative Assembly of Ontario|Ontario Legislature]]. Covering eighteen rectangular townships in [[Central Ontario]], the Park was created to provide a space dedicated to recreation, wildlife and watershed protection, though logging operations continued to be permitted.{{sfnb|Wadland|2002|p=95}} Thomson learned of the Park from fellow artist Tom McLean.{{sfnb|Hill|2002|p=118}}{{sfnb|Wadland|2002|p=94}}  In May 1912, aged 34, he first visited the Park, venturing through the area on a canoe trip with his Grip colleague H. B. (Ben) Jackson.<ref>{{plainlist|
* {{harvp|Hunter|2002|p=25}}
* {{harvp|Klages|2016|p=21}}
* {{harvp|Silcox|2006|p=20}}
* {{harvp|Silcox|2015|p=[https://www.aci-iac.ca/art-books/tom-thomson/biography/#discovering-algonquin-park 10]}}
* {{harvp|Stacey|2002|p=57}}}}</ref> Together, they took the [[Grand Trunk Railway]] from Toronto to Scotia Junction, then transferred to the [[Ottawa, Arnprior and Parry Sound Railway]], arriving at [[Canoe Lake (Nipissing District)|Canoe Lake]] Station.{{sfnb|Wadland|2002|p=94}} McLean introduced Thomson to the Park superintendent, G. W. Barlett.{{sfnb|Hill|2002|p=118}}{{sfnb|Addison|Harwood|1969|p=88n4}} Thomson and Jackson later met ranger Harry (Bud) Callighen while they camped nearby on Smoke Lake.{{sfnb|Hill|2002|p=118}}{{sfnb|Addison|1974|p=75}}

It was also at this time that Thomson acquired his first sketching equipment.{{sfnb|Hill|2002|p=118}}{{sfnb|Murray|2011|p=3}} He did not yet take painting seriously. According to Jackson, Thomson did not think "his work would ever be taken seriously; in fact, he used to chuckle over the idea".{{sfnb|Hunter|2002|pp=25–26}} Instead, they spent most of their time fishing,{{sfnb|Hunter|2002|pp=25–26}} except for "a few notes, skylines and colour effects".{{sfnb|Hill|2002|p=118}}

During the same trip, Thomson read [[Izaak Walton]]'s 1653 fishing guide, ''[[The Compleat Angler]]''.{{sfnb|Hunter|2002|p=26}} Primarily a fisherman's bible, the book also provided a philosophy of how to live, similar to the one described in [[Henry David Thoreau]]'s 1854 book, ''[[Walden|Walden, or Life in the Woods]]'', a reflection on [[simple living]] in natural surroundings.{{sfnb|Hunter|2002|p=26}} His time in Algonquin Park gave him an ideal setting to imitate Walton's "contemplative" life.{{sfnb|Hunter|2002|p=27}} Ben Jackson wrote:

{{quote|Tom was never understood by lots of people, was very quiet, modest and, as a friend of mine spoke of him, a gentle soul. He cared nothing for social life, but with one or two companions on a sketching and fishing trip with his pipe and [[Hudson Bay]] tobacco going, he was a delightful companion. If a party or the boys got a little loud or rough Tom would get his sketching kit and wander off alone. At times he liked to be that way, wanted to be by himself commune {{sic}} with nature.{{sfnb|Hunter|2002|p=27}}}}

Upon returning to Toronto, Jackson published an article about his and Thomson's experience in the Park in the ''[[The Toronto World|Toronto Sunday World]]'', included in which were several illustrations.{{sfnb|Hill|2002|p=118}} After this initial experience, Thomson and another colleague, William Broadhead, went on a two-month expedition, going up the [[Spanish River (Ontario)|Spanish River]] and into Mississagi Forest Reserve (today [[Mississagi Provincial Park]]).{{sfnb|Hunter|2002|p=27}} Thomson's transition from commercial art towards his own original style of painting became apparent around this time.{{sfnb|Silcox|2015|p=[https://www.aci-iac.ca/art-books/tom-thomson/biography/#discovering-algonquin-park 10]}}{{sfnb|Silcox|2006|p=23}} Much of his artwork from this trip, mainly oil sketches and photographs, was lost during two canoe spills;{{sfnb|Silcox|2015|p=[https://www.aci-iac.ca/art-books/tom-thomson/biography/#discovering-algonquin-park 10]}} the first was on Green Lake in a rain squall and the second in a series of rapids.{{sfnb|Hill|2002|p=119}}{{efn|group=note|Thomson wrote in a letter to his friend M. J. (John) McRuer: {{quote|We started in at Bisco and took a long trip on the lakes around there going up the [[Spanish River (Ontario)|Spanish River]] and over into the Mississauga <nowiki>[</nowiki>[[Mississagi River|Mississagi]]<nowiki>]</nowiki> water we got a great many good snapshots of game—mostly moose and some sketches, ''but'' we had a dump in the forty-mile rapids which is near the end of our trip and lost most of our stuff—we only saved 2 rolls of film out of about 14 dozen. Outside of that we had a peach of a time as the Mississauga is considered the finest canoe trip in the world.{{sfnb|Murray|2002a|p=297}}}}}}

In fall 1912, Albert Robson, Grip's art director, moved to the design firm Rous & Mann.{{sfnb|Silcox|2015|p=[https://www.aci-iac.ca/art-books/tom-thomson/biography/#graphic-design-in-toronto 9]}} A month after returning to Toronto, Thomson followed Robson and left Grip to join Rous & Mann too.{{sfnb|Wadland|2002|p=95}}{{sfnb|Stacey|2002|p=58}}{{sfnb|Klages|2016|p=23}} They were soon joined by Varley, Carmichael and Lismer.{{sfnb|Hill|2002|p=119}} Robson later spoke favourably of Thomson's loyalty, calling him "a most diligent, reliable and capable craftsman".<ref>{{harvp|Robson|1932|p=138}} quoted in {{harvp|Stacey|2002|p=53}}</ref> Robson's success in attracting great talent was well understood.{{sfnb|Stacey|2002|p=57-58}} Employee Leonard Rossell believed that the key to Robson's success "was that the artists felt that he was interested in them personally and did all he could to further their progress. Those who worked there were all allowed time off to pursue their studies&nbsp;... Tom Thomson, so far as I know, never took definite lessons from anyone, yet he progressed quicker than any of us. But what he did was probably of more advantage to him. He took several months off in the summer and spent them in Algonquin Park."<ref>{{harvp|Rossell|c. 1951|p=3}} quoted in {{harvp|Stacey|2002|p=58}}</ref>
[[File:Tom Thomson, Northern Lake.jpg|thumb|''Northern Lake'', Winter 1912–13. 71.7 x 102.4 cm. Art Gallery of Ontario, Toronto]]

In October, MacDonald introduced Thomson to Dr. [[James MacCallum]].{{sfnb|Hill|2002|p=119}} A frequent visitor to the [[Ontario Society of Artists]]' (OSA) exhibitions, MacCallum was admitted to the Arts and Letters Club in January 1912. There, he met artists such as [[John William Beatty]], [[Arthur Heming]], MacDonald and Harris.{{sfnb|Hill|2002|p=119}} MacCallum eventually persuaded Thomson to leave Rous and Mann and start a painting career.{{sfnb|Wadland|2002|p=95}} In October 1913, MacCallum introduced Thomson to [[A. Y. Jackson]], later a founder of the Group of Seven.{{sfnb|Hill|2002|p=122}} MacCallum recognized Thomson's and Jackson's talents and offered to cover their expenses for one year if they committed themselves to painting full time.{{sfnb|Silcox|2006|p=21}}{{sfnb|Silcox|2015|p=[https://www.aci-iac.ca/art-books/tom-thomson/biography/#discovering-algonquin-park 11]}} MacCallum and Jackson both encouraged Thomson to "take up painting seriously, [but] he showed no enthusiasm. The chances of earning a livelihood by it did not appear to him promising. He was sensitive and independent, and feared he might become an object of patronage."{{sfnb|Hill|2002|p=122}} MacCallum wrote that when he first saw Thomson's sketches, he recognized their "truthfulness, their feeling and their sympathy with the grim fascinating northland&nbsp;... they made me feel that the North had gripped Thomson as it had gripped me since I was eleven when I first sailed and paddled through its silent places." He described Thomson's paintings as "dark, muddy in colour, tight and not wanting in technical defects".{{sfnb|MacCallum|1918|p=376}} After Thomson's death, MacCallum helped preserve and advocate for his work.{{sfnb|Silcox|2015|p=[https://www.aci-iac.ca/art-books/tom-thomson/biography/#discovering-algonquin-park 11]}}

Thomson accepted MacCallum's offer under the same terms offered to Jackson.{{sfnb|Hill|2002|p=122}} He travelled around Ontario with his colleagues, especially to the wilderness of Ontario, which was to become a major source of inspiration. Regarding Algonquin Park, he wrote in a letter to MacCallum: "The best I can do does not do the place much justice in the way of beauty."{{sfnb|Murray|2002a|p=298}} He ventured to rural areas near Toronto and tried to capture the surrounding nature. He may have worked as a fire ranger on the [[Mattagami First Nation|Mattagami reserve]].{{sfnb|Murray|2002b|p=312}} Addison and Little suggest that he guided fishing tours,{{sfnb|Addison|1974|p=18}}{{sfnb|Little|1970|p=13}} although Hill finds this unlikely since Thomson had only spent a few weeks in the Park the previous year.{{sfnb|Hill|2002|p=121}} Thomson became as familiar with logging scenes as with nature in the Park and painted them both.{{sfnb|Silcox|2015|p=[https://www.aci-iac.ca/art-books/tom-thomson/significance-and-critical-issues/#the-artist-and-nature 58]}}

While returning to Toronto in November 1912, Thomson stopped in [[Huntsville, Ontario|Huntsville]].{{sfnb|Hill|2002|p=121}}{{sfnb|Addison|1974|pp=25–26}} The visit was possibly to meet with Winfred Trainor, a woman whose family owned a cottage on Canoe Lake in Algonquin Park. Trainor was later rumoured to have been engaged to Thomson with a wedding planned for the late 1917, although little is known about their relationship.{{sfnb|Silcox|2015|p=[https://www.aci-iac.ca/art-books/tom-thomson/biography/#thomsons-early-paintings 12]}}{{sfnb|King|2010|pp=169–70}}{{efn|group=note|For more regarding Thomson's possible romantic relationship with Trainor, refer to {{harvp|MacGregor|2010}}.}}

Thomson first exhibited with the OSA in March 1913, selling his painting ''Northern Lake'' (1912–13) to the [[Government of Ontario|Ontario Government]] for $250 ({{Inflation|CA|250|1914|fmt=eq|r=-2|cursign=[[Canadian Dollar|CAD$]]}}).{{sfnb|Hill|2002|p=120}}{{sfnb|Silcox|2015|p=[https://www.aci-iac.ca/art-books/tom-thomson/biography/#painting-full-time 12]}} The sale afforded him time to paint and sketch through the summer and fall of 1913.{{sfnb|Stacey|2002|p=60}}

{{Quote box|align=left|width=85%|quote="[[Oil sketch|Sketch]]" indicates that the work is a smaller [[Oil paint|oil]] work, generally on [[Panel painting|wood panel]]. The dimensions are often close to 21.6 × 26.7 cm (8½ x 10½ in.) but sometimes as small as 12.8 x 18.2 cm (5<small>{{frac|1|16}}</small> x 7<small>{{frac|3|16}}</small> in.).}}

