====Early recognition (1914–15)====
{{see also|Northern River (painting)|Spring Ice|Studio Building (Toronto)}}

[[File:The Studio Building 2, Toronto, Canada.jpg|thumb|left|The [[Studio Building (Toronto)|Studio Building]] in Toronto, where Thomson lived and worked from January 1914 through November 1915.]]

Thomson often experienced self-doubt. A. Y. Jackson recalled that in the fall of 1914, Thomson threw his sketch box into the woods out of frustration,{{sfnb|Jackson|1958|p=31}} and was "so shy he could hardly be induced to show his sketches".{{sfnb|Hill|2002|p=117}} Harris expressed similar sentiments, writing that Thomson "had no opinion of his own work", and would even throw burnt matches at his paintings.{{sfnb|Hill|2002|pp=117, 117n36}} Several of the canvases he sent to exhibitions remained unsigned.{{efn|group=note|Unsigned paintings exhibited during Thomson's lifetime include: ''Northern Lake'' (1912–13); ''[[:File:Tom Thomson Morning Cloud.jpg|Morning Cloud]]''; ''Moonlight'' (1913–14); ''[[:File:Tom Thomson Split Rock, Georgian Bay.jpg|Split Rock, Georgian Bay]]''; ''Canadian Wildflowers''; ''Moonlight'' (1915); and ''[[:File:Tom Thomson October.jpg|October]]''.{{sfnb|Hill|2002|p=117n35}}}} If someone praised one of his sketches, he immediately gave it to them as a gift.{{sfnb|Hill|2002|p=117}} A turning point in his career came in 1914, when the [[National Gallery of Canada]], under the directorship of Eric Brown, began to acquire his paintings. Although the money was not enough to live on, the recognition was unheard of for an unknown artist.{{sfnb|Silcox|2015|p=[https://www.aci-iac.ca/art-books/tom-thomson/biography/#a-startling-debut 13]}}

For several years he shared a studio and living quarters with fellow artists, initially living in the [[Studio Building (Toronto)|Studio Building]] with Jackson in January 1914. Jackson described the Studio Building as "a lively centre for new ideas, experiments, discussions, plans for the future and visions of an art inspired by the Canadian countryside".{{sfnb|Jackson|1958|p=27}} It was there that Thomson, "after much self-deprecation, finally submitted to becoming a full-time artist".<ref>{{harvp|Jackson|1933|p=138}} quoted in {{harvp|Roza|1997|pp=20–21}}</ref> They split the rent—$22 a month—on the ground floor while construction on the rest of the building was finished.{{sfnb|Silcox|2006|p=127}} After Jackson moved out in December to go to [[Montreal]], Carmichael took his place.{{sfnb|Silcox|2006|p=127}}{{sfnb|Murray|2006|p=17}}{{sfnb|Hill|2002|p=128}} Thomson and Carmichael shared a studio space through the winter.{{sfnb|King|2010|pp=154–59}} On March 3, 1914, Thomson was nominated as a member of the OSA by Lismer and T. G. Greene. He was elected on the 17th. He did not participate in any of their activities, however, beyond sending paintings for annual exhibitions.{{sfnb|Hill|2002|p=117}} Harris described Thomson's strange working hours years later:

{{quote|When he was in Toronto, Tom rarely left the shack in the daytime and then only when it was absolutely necessary. He took his exercise at night. He would put on his snowshoes and tramp the length of the [[Rosedale, Toronto|Rosedale]] ravine and out into the country, and return before dawn.<ref>{{harvp|Harris|1964}} quoted in {{harvp|Silcox|2006|p=127}}</ref>}}

[[File:Tom Thomson with fish.jpg|thumb|Thomson with his catch at [[Canoe Lake (Nipissing District)|Canoe Lake]], [[Algonquin Provincial Park|Algonquin Park]], {{circa|lk=no|1915}}]]

In late April 1914, Thomson arrived in Algonquin Park, where he was joined by Lismer on May 9. They camped on Molly's Island in Smoke Lake, travelling to Canoe, Smoke, Ragged, Crown and Wolf Lakes.{{sfnb|Hill|2002|p=124}} He spent his spring and summer divided between [[Georgian Bay]] and Algonquin Park, visiting James MacCallum by canoe. His travels during this time have proved difficult to discern, with such a large amount of ground covered in such a short time, painting the [[French River (Ontario)|French River]], [[Byng Inlet (Ontario)|Byng Inlet]], [[Parry Sound, Ontario|Parry Sound]] and Go-Home Bay from May 24 through August 10.{{sfnb|Wadland|2002|p=105}} H. A. Callighen, a park ranger, wrote in his journal that Thomson and Lismer left Algonquin Park on May 24.{{sfnb|Hill|2002|p=125}} By May 30, Thomson was at Parry Sound and on June 1 was camped at the French River with MacCallum.{{sfnb|Hill|2002|p=125}}{{sfnb|Wadland|2002|p=105n70}}

Art historian [[Joan Murray (art historian)|Joan Murray]] noted that Thomson was at Go-Home Bay for the next two months, or at least until August 10 when he was seen again in Algonquin Park by Callighan.{{sfnb|Murray|2002b|p=313}} According to Wadland, if this timeline is correct, it would require "an extraordinary canoeist&nbsp;... The difficulty is augmented by the fact of stopping to sketch at intervals along the way."{{sfnb|Wadland|2002|p=105n70}} Wadland suggested that Thomson may have travelled by train at some point and by [[steamship]] thereafter.{{sfnb|Wadland|2002|p=105}} Addison and Harwood instead said that Thomson had found much of the inland "monotonously flat" and the rapids "ordinary".{{sfnb|Addison|Harwood|1969|p=32}} Wadland found this characterization unhelpful, pointing out that the rapids Thomson had faced were hardly "ordinary".{{sfnb|Wadland|2002|p=105n70}}

[[File:Tom Thomson Cottage on a Rocky Shore.jpg|thumb|left|''Cottage on a Rocky Shore'', Summer 1914. Sketch. National Gallery of Canada, Ottawa]]

MacCallum provided specific dates for two of Thomson's paintings—May 30 and June 1 for ''[[:File:Tom Thomson Parry Sound Harbour.jpg|Parry Sound Harbour]]'' and ''[[:File:Tom Thomson Spring, French River.jpg|Spring, French River]]'', respectively.{{sfnb|Hill|2002|p=125}}{{sfnb|Murray|2004|p=108}} These are some of the only instances of precise dating for his work.{{sfnb|Hill|2002|pp=125–26}} In addition, ''Cottage on a Rocky Shore'' is a depiction of MacCallum's cottage contrasted with the vast expanse of sky and water. ''[[:File:Tom Thomson Evening, Pine Island.jpg|Evening, Pine Island]]'' is of a nearby island MacCallum took Thomson to visit.{{sfnb|Hill|2002|p=126}} He continued to paint around the islands until he departed, probably because he found MacCallum's cottage too demanding socially, writing to Varley that it was "too much like north Rosedale".{{sfnb|Hill|2002|p=126}}{{sfnb|Waddington|Waddington|2016|p=131}}

Thomson continued canoeing alone until he met with A. Y. Jackson at Canoe Lake in mid-September. Though [[World War I]] had erupted that year, he and Jackson went on a canoe trip, in October meeting up with Varley and his wife Maud, as well as Lismer and his wife Esther, and daughter Marjorie.{{sfnb|Hill|2002|p=126}} This marked the first time three Group of Seven members painted together, and the only time they worked with Thomson.{{sfnb|Silcox|2006|p=23}}{{sfnb|Silcox|2015|p=[https://www.aci-iac.ca/art-books/tom-thomson/biography/#a-startling-debut 13]}} In his 1958 autobiography, ''A Painter's Country'', A. Y. Jackson wrote that, "Had it not been for the war, the Group [of Seven] would have formed several years earlier and it would have included Thomson."{{sfnb|Jackson|1958|pp=53–54}}

Why Thomson did not serve in the war has been debated.{{sfnb|Hunter|2002|p=40}} Mark Robinson and Thomson's family said that he was turned down after multiple attempts to enlist, likely due to his poor health and age but also possibly because he had [[flat feet]].{{sfnb|Silcox|Town|2017|p=41}}{{sfnb|Silcox|2006|pp=107–08}}{{sfnb|Silcox|2015|p=[https://www.aci-iac.ca/art-books/tom-thomson/biography/#a-startling-debut 13]}} Blodwen Davies wrote that Thomson's artist friends tried to convince him to not risk his life, but he decided to secretly volunteer anyway.<ref>{{harvp|Davies|1930|pp=29–31}} quoted in {{harvp|Hunter|2002|p=40}}</ref> Andrew Hunter has found this scenario to be improbable, especially given that other artist friends ''did'' volunteer for the war, such as A. Y. Jackson.{{sfnb|Hunter|2002|p=40}} Thomson's sister suggested that he was a pacifist and that "he hated war and said simply in 1914 that he never would kill anyone but would like to help in a hospital, if accepted".<ref>{{harvp|Thomson|1956|pp=21–24}} quoted in {{harvp|Hunter|2002|p=40}}</ref> William Colgate wrote that Thomson "brooded much upon" the war and that "he himself did not enlist. Rumour has it that he tried, and failed to pass the doctor. This is doubtful."<ref>{{harvp|Colgate|1946|p=15}} quoted in {{harvp|Hunter|2002|p=40}}</ref> Edward Godin, a companion, said "We had many discussions on the war. As I remember it he did not think that Canada should be involved. He was very outspoken in his opposition to Government patronage. Especially in the Militia. I do not think that we would offer himself for service. I know up until that time he had not tried to enlist."{{sfnb|Hunter|2002|p=40}} There is only one verifiable example of Thomson's opinion on the war, taken from a letter he wrote to J. E. H. MacDonald in 1915:

{{quote|As with yourself, I can't get used to the idea of [A. Y.] Jackson being in the machine and it is rotten that in this so-called civilized age that such things can exist, but since this war has started it will have to go on until one side wins out, and of course there is no doubt which side it will be, and we will see Jackson back on the job once more.{{sfnb|Murray|2002a|p=300–01}}{{sfnb|Hunter|2002|p=41}}}}

[[File:Thomson, In Algonquin Park.jpg|thumb|''In Algonquin Park'', Winter 1914–15. 63.2 × 81.1 cm. McMichael Canadian Art Collection, Kleinburg]]

With MacCallum's year of financial support over, Thomson's financial future became uncertain.{{sfnb|Hill|2002|p=128}} He briefly looked into applying for a position as a park ranger, but balked after seeing that it could take months for the application to go through. Instead, he considered working in an engraving shop over the winter.{{sfnb|Hill|2002|p=126}} He made little effort to sell his paintings, preferring to give them away, though he brought in some money from the paintings he sold.{{sfnb|Silcox|2015|p=[https://www.aci-iac.ca/art-books/tom-thomson/biography/#gathering-momentum 14]}} In mid-November, he donated ''In Algonquin Park'' to an exhibition organized to raise money for the [[Canadian Patriotic Fund]]. It was sold to Marion Long for $50 ({{Inflation|CA|50|1914|fmt=eq|r=-2|cursign=CAD$}}).{{sfnb|Hill|2002|p=128}}

In the spring of 1915, Thomson returned to Algonquin Park earlier than he had in any previous year and had already painted twenty-eight sketches by April 22. From April through July, he spent much of his time fishing, assisting groups on several different lakes, and sketching when he had time.{{sfnb|Hill|2002|p=131}} In July, he was invited to send paintings to the [[Nova Scotia]] Provincial Exhibition in September.{{sfnb|Hill|2002|p=133}} Because he was in Algonquin Park, his friends selected three works to send—two unidentified works from 1914 and the sketch ''Canadian Wildflowers''.{{sfnb|Hill|2002|p=133}} From the end of September to mid-October, he spent his time at Mowat, a village on the north end of Canoe Lake.{{sfnb|Wadland|2002|p=102}} By November, he was at Round Lake with Tom Wattie and Dr. Robert McComb.<ref>{{harvp|Ghent|1949}} quoted in {{harvp|Hill|2002|p=131}}</ref>{{sfnb|Addison|Harwood|1969|p=46}} In late November, he returned to Toronto and moved into a shack behind the Studio Building that Harris and MacCallum fixed up for him,{{sfnb|Addison|Harwood|1969|p=84}}{{sfnb|Little|1970|p=179}} renting it for $1 a month.{{sfnb|Silcox|2015|p=[https://www.aci-iac.ca/art-books/tom-thomson/biography/#painting-full-time 13]}}{{efn|group=note|In his 1959 piece, "My Memories of Tom Thomson", [[Thoreau MacDonald]] cited November 1915 as when Thomson moved into the shack behind the [[Studio Building (Toronto)|Studio Building]].{{sfnb|Hill|2002|p=132n119}} Most sources agree with this, including Charles Hill,{{sfnb|Hill|2002|p=132}} William Little{{sfnb|Little|1970|p=179}} and Addison & Harwood.{{sfnb|Addison|Harwood|1969|p=84}} David Silcox has written that the move happened in either late 1914{{sfnb|Silcox|2006|p=127}} or early 1915.{{sfnb|Silcox|2006|p=127}}{{sfnb|Silcox|2015|pp=[https://www.aci-iac.ca/art-books/tom-thomson/biography/#painting-full-time 12–13]}}}}

In 1915, MacCallum commissioned MacDonald, Lismer and Thomson to paint decorative panels for his cottage on Go-Home Bay. In October of that year, MacDonald went up to take dimensions.{{sfnb|Hill|2002|p=136}}{{sfnb|Landry|1990|p=26}} Thomson produced four panels which were probably meant to go over the windows. In April 1916, when MacDonald and Lismer went to install them, they found that MacDonald's measurements were incorrect and the panels did not fit.{{sfnb|Reid|1970|p=93}}{{sfnb|Stacey|Bishop|1996|p=119}}{{efn|group=note|MacDonald's measurements were 44½ × 37", but the panels installed were 27 × 37". The panels Thomson produced were 47½ × 38".{{sfnb|Hill|2002|p=136n134}}{{sfnb|Reid|1969|pp=49, 69}}}}

<gallery widths="200px" heights="200px" perrow="5">
File:Tom Thomson Canoe Lake Spring 1914.jpg|''Canoe Lake'', Spring 1914. Sketch. Tom Thomson Art Gallery, Owen Sound
File:Tom Thomson Smoke Lake.jpg|''Smoke Lake'', Summer 1915. Sketch. McMichael Canadian Art Collection, Kleinburg
File:Thomson, Fire-Swept Hills.jpg|''Fire-Swept Hills'', Summer or fall 1915. Sketch. Art Gallery of Ontario, Toronto
File:Tom Thomson - Autumn Foliage - Google Art Project.jpg|''Autumn Foliage'', Fall or winter 1915. Sketch. Art Gallery of Ontario, Toronto
File:Tom Thomson, Spring Ice.jpg|''[[Spring Ice]]'', Winter 1915–16. 72.0 × 102.3 cm. National Gallery of Canada, Ottawa
</gallery>

====Artistic peak (1916–17)====

In March 1916, Thomson exhibited four canvases with the OSA: ''In the Northland'' (at that time titled ''The Birches''), ''[[Spring Ice]]'', ''Moonlight'' and ''October'' (then titled ''The Hardwoods''), all of which were painted over the winter of 1915–16. Sir Edmund Walker and Eric Brown of the National Gallery of Canada wanted to purchase ''In the Northland'', but Montreal trustee Dr. Francis Shepherd convinced them to purchase ''Spring Ice'' instead.{{sfnb|Hill|2002|p=136}} The reception of Thomson's paintings at this time was mixed. Margaret Fairbairn of the ''[[Toronto Star|Toronto Daily Star]]'' wrote, "Mr. Tom Thomson's 'The Birches' and 'The Hardwoods' show a fondness for intense yellows and orange and strong blue, altogether a fearless use of violent colour which can scarcely be called pleasing, and yet which seems an exaggeration of a truthful feeling that time will temper."<ref>{{harvp|Fairbairn|1916}} quoted in {{harvp|Hill|2002|p=136}}</ref> A more favourable take came from artist [[Edmund Wyly Grier|Wyly Grier]] in ''[[The Christian Science Monitor]]'':

[[File:Tom Thomson In the Northland.jpg|thumb|left|''In the Northland'', Winter 1915–1916.{{efn|group=note|''In the Northland'' was originally titled ''The Birches''.{{sfnb|Hill|2002|p=136}} All of Thomson's canvases from the winter of 1916–17 were titled after his death.{{sfnb|Hill|2002|p=139}}}} 101.7 x 114.5 cm. [[Montreal Museum of Fine Arts]], [[Montreal]]]]

{{quote|Tom Thomson again reveals his capacity to be modern and remain individual. His early pictures—in which the quality of naivete had all the genuineness of the effort of the tyro and was not the counterfeit of it which is so much in evidence in the intensely rejuvenated works of the highly sophisticated—showed the faculty for affectionate and truthful record by a receptive eye and faithful hand; but his work today has reached higher levels of technical accomplishment. His ''Moonlight'', ''Spring Ice'' and ''The Birches'' are among his best.{{sfnb|Hill|2002|pp=136–37}}}} In ''The Canadian Courier'', painter [[Estelle Muriel Kerr|Estelle Kerr]] also spoke positively, describing Thomson as "one of the most promising of Canadian painters who follows the impressionist movement and his work reveals himself to be a fine colourist, a clever technician, and a truthful interpreter of the north land in its various aspects".<ref>{{harvp|Kerr|1916|p=13}} quoted in {{harvp|Hill|2002|p=137}}</ref>

In 1916, Thomson left for Algonquin Park earlier than any previous year, evidenced by the large number of snow studies he produced at this time.{{sfnb|Hill|2002|p=137}} In April or early May, MacCallum, Harris and his cousin Chester Harris joined Thomson at Cauchon Lake for a canoe trip.{{sfnb|Hill|2002|p=137}}{{sfnb|Silcox|2015|p=[https://www.aci-iac.ca/art-books/tom-thomson/biography/#at-full-speed 16]}} After MacCallum and Chester left, Harris and Thomson paddled together to Aura Lee Lake.{{sfnb|Reid|1970|p=126}} Thomson produced many sketches which varied in composition, although they all had vivid colour and thickly-applied paint.{{sfnb|Silcox|2015|p=[https://www.aci-iac.ca/art-books/tom-thomson/biography/#at-full-speed 16]}} MacCallum was present when he painted his ''Sketch for "The Jack Pine"'', writing that the tree fell over onto Thomson before the sketch was completed. He added that Harris thought the tree killed Thomson, "but he sprang up and continued painting".{{sfnb|Hill|2002|p=137}}

[[File:Thomson, Tea Lake Dam.jpg|thumb|''Tea Lake Dam'', Summer 1917. Sketch. McMichael Canadian Art Collection, Kleinburg]]

At the end of May, Thomson took a job as a fire ranger stationed at [[Achray, Ontario|Achray]] on [[Grand Lake (Nipissing)|Grand Lake]] with Ed Godin. He followed the [[John Rudolphus Booth#Lumber|Booth Lumber Company]]'s [[Log driving|log drive]] down the [[Petawawa River]] to the north end of the park.{{sfnb|Hill|2002|pp=137–38}} He found that fire ranging and painting did not mix well together,{{sfnb|Hill|2002|p=138}} writing, "[I] have done very little sketching this summer as the two jobs don't fit in... When we are travelling two go together, one for canoe and the other the pack. And there's no place for a sketch outfit when your {{sic}} fire ranging. We are not fired yet but I am hoping to get put off right away."{{sfnb|Murray|2002a|pp=302–03}} He likely returned to Toronto in late October or early November.{{sfnb|Hill|2002|p=138}}

Over the following winter, encouragement from Harris, MacDonald and MacCallum saw Thomson move into the most productive portion of his career,{{sfnb|Silcox|2006|p=20}} with Thomson writing in a letter that he "got quite a lot done".{{sfnb|Murray|2002a|pp=303–04}} Despite this, he did not submit any paintings to the OSA exhibition in the spring of 1917.{{sfnb|Hill|2002|p=139}} It was during this time that he produced many of his most famous works, including ''[[The Jack Pine]]'' and ''[[The West Wind (painting)|The West Wind]]''.{{sfnb|Silcox|2015|p=[https://www.aci-iac.ca/art-books/tom-thomson/biography/#at-full-speed 17]}} Dr. MacCallum suggested that several canvas works were unfinished, including ''Woodland Waterfall'', ''The Pointers'' and ''The Drive''.<ref>{{harvp|MacCallum|1918|pp=375–85}} quoted in {{harvp|Hill|2002|p=139}}</ref> [[Barker Fairley]] similarly described ''The West Wind'' as unfinished.<ref>{{harvp|Fairley|1920|p=246}} quoted in {{harvp|Hill|2002|p=139}}</ref> Charles Hill has written that there are no reasons to believe ''Woodland Waterfall'' was unfinished.{{sfnb|Hill|2002|p=139}} Similarly, while it has sometimes been suggested that ''The Drive'' was modified after Thomson's death,<ref>{{harvp|Forsey|1975|p=188}} quoted in {{harvp|Hill|2002|p=139}}</ref> a reproduction from 1918 displays no discernible differences.{{sfnb|Hill|2002|pp=140, 140n167}}

Thomson returned to Canoe Lake at the beginning of April, arriving early enough to paint the remaining snow and the ice breaking up on the surrounding lakes. He had little money but wrote that he could manage for about a year. On April 28, 1917, he received a guide's licence. Unlike previous years, he remained at Mowat with Lieutenant Crombine and his wife, Daphne. Thomson invited Daphne Crombie to select something from his spring sketches as a gift, and she selected ''[[:File:Thomson, Path Behind Mowat Lodge.jpg|Path Behind Mowat Lodge]]''.{{sfnb|Hill|2002|p=141}}

Besides the deep love he had come to develop for Algonquin Park, Thomson was beginning to show an eagerness to depict areas beyond the park and explore other northern subjects.{{sfnb|Silcox|2015|p=[https://www.aci-iac.ca/art-books/tom-thomson/biography#final-spring 18]}} In an April 1917 letter to his brother-in-law, he wrote that he was considering taking the [[Canadian Northern Railway]] west so he could paint the [[Canadian Rockies]] in July and August.{{sfnb|Murray|1999|p=122}}{{sfnb|Murray|2002a|pp=304–05}} A. Y. Jackson suggested Thomson would have traveled even further north, just as the other members of the Group of Seven eventually did.{{sfnb|Murray|1999|p=122}}

