</gallery>

====People====

[[File:Tom Thomson Poacher.jpg|thumb|''The Poacher'', Spring 1916. Sketch. Art Gallery of Ontario, Toronto]]

Thomson, like most of the members of the Group of Seven, rarely painted people.{{sfnb|Hunter|2002|p=32}}{{sfnb|Silcox|2006|p=76}}{{efn|group=note|Notable exceptions are [[Frederick Varley]] and [[Frank Johnston (artist)|Frank Johnston]], with Varley's main interest being people, faces and figures.{{sfnb|Silcox|2006|p=76}}{{sfnb|Silcox|Town|2017|p=124}} At the beginning of his career, [[Lawren Harris]] captured people in nearly all of his depictions of Toronto and did several portraits, but later moved on to only depicting landscapes. [[Edwin Holgate]] painted the female figure and completed several [[Nude (art)|nudes]].{{sfnb|Silcox|2006|p=76}}}} When he did, the human subject was usually someone close to him personally, such as the depiction of Shannon Fraser in ''In the Sugar Bush''. The figure in ''The Poacher'' is recorded deliberately, including his hat, hunting vest and blue shirt. The hot [[Barbecue grill#Charcoal grills|coal grill]] in front of him is drying his [[poaching|poach]]—likely [[venison]].{{sfnb|Murray|2011|p=96}} Harold Town observed that both Thomson and Canadian artist [[David Milne (artist)|David Milne]] "shared in common a similar inability to draw the human figure",{{sfnb|Wadland|2002|p=99}} something professor John Wadland thought was "embarrassingly evident" in several of Thomson's portraits.{{sfnb|Wadland|2002|p=99}}

Town described paintings like ''Man with Axe (Lowery Dixon) Splitting Wood'' as stiff, yet still held together in a cohesive crudity. He described ''Figure of a Lady, Laura'' differently, interpreting it as a tender work, "well-designed and plainly expressed, this loving picture is so secure in intention that it survives, indeed triumphs, over the severe cracking of the paint".{{sfnb|Silcox|Town|2017|p=124}} Thomson's most successful attempts at capturing people typically feature [[Staffage|figures far off in the distance]], allowing them to blend in to the scene. This is apparent in paintings like ''Little Cauchon Lake'', ''Bateaux'', ''The Drive'', ''The Pointers'' and ''[[:File:Tom Thomson Tea Lake Dam.jpg|Tea Lake Dam]]''.{{sfnb|Hunter|2002|p=32}}

