==Legacy and influence==
{{main|Death and legacy of Tom Thomson}}

[[File:Tom Thomson, standing on a rock fishing in moving water.jpg|thumb|Thomson fishing at Tea Lake Dam in [[Algonquin Park]], {{circa|lk=no|1915}}]]

Since his death, Thomson's work has grown in value and popularity. Group of Seven member Arthur Lismer wrote that he "is the manifestation of the Canadian character".<ref>{{harvp|Lismer|1934|pp=163–64}} quoted in {{harvp|Hunter|2002|p=35}}</ref> Another contemporaneous Canadian painter, David Milne, wrote to [[National Gallery of Canada#Directors|National Gallery of Canada Director]] H. O. McCurry in 1930, "Your Canadian art apparently, for now at least, went down in Canoe Lake. Tom Thomson still stands as ''the'' Canadian painter, harsh, brilliant, brittle, uncouth, not only most Canadian but most creative. How the few things of his stick in one's mind."{{sfnb|Dejardin|2018|pp=17, 194}} For Canadian artists [[Roy Kiyooka]] and [[Dennis Lee (author)|Dennis Lee]], he is a "haunting presence" and "embodies the Canadian artistic identity".{{sfnb|Grace|2004a|p=96}}

As of 2015, the highest price achieved by a Thomson sketch was ''[[:File:Tom Thomson Early Spring, Canoe Lake.jpg|Early Spring, Canoe Lake]]'', which sold in 2009 for [[Canadian dollar|CAD]]$2,749,500. Few major canvases remain in private collections, making the record unlikely to be broken.{{sfnb|Silcox|2015|p=[https://www.aci-iac.ca/art-books/tom-thomson/significance-and-critical-issues/#thomson-and-the-art-market 66]}} One example of the demand his work has achieved is the previously lost ''[[:File:Tom Thomson Sketch for Lake in Algonquin Park.jpg|Sketch for Lake in Algonquin Park]]''.  This was discovered in an [[Edmonton]] basement in 2018 and went on to sell for nearly half a million dollars at a Toronto auction.{{sfnb|Vikander|2018}}{{sfnb|The Canadian Press|2018}} The increased value of his work has led to the discovery of numerous [[art forgery|forgeries]] on the market.{{sfnb|Silcox|Town|2017|p=182}}{{sfnb|Silcox|2015|p=[https://www.aci-iac.ca/art-books/tom-thomson/style-and-technique/#surface-preparation 74]}}{{sfnb|Dellandrea|2017}}

In 1967, the Tom Thomson Art Gallery opened in Owen Sound.<ref>{{cite web|title=Tom Thomson Art Gallery|url=https://www.owensound.ca/en/exploring/ttag-about.aspx|publisher=City of Owen Sound}}</ref> In 1968, Thomson's shack from behind the Studio Building was moved to the McMichael Canadian Art Collection in Kleinburg.{{sfnb|Dexter|1968}} Many of his works are also on display at the National Gallery of Canada in Ottawa, the Art Gallery of Ontario, and the McMichael Canadian Art Collection in Kleinburg, Ontario.{{sfnb|Silcox|Town|2017|p=181}} His influence can be seen in the work of later Canadian artists, including [[Joyce Wieland]].{{sfnb|Stanners|2017}} In 2004, another historical marker honouring Thomson was moved from its previous location nearer the centre of Leith to the graveyard in which he is now buried. The grave site has become popular spot for visitors to the area with many fans of his work leaving pennies or art supplies behind as tribute.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.heritagemeaford.com/heritage-church.php?mid=1|title=Leith United Church {{!}} Heritage Meaford|website=www.heritagemeaford.com|access-date=January 16, 2018}}</ref>

===The outdoorsman===
{{Main|Death and legacy of Tom Thomson#The outdoorsman}}

Though he is most known for his painting, Thomson is often mythologized as a veritable [[Outdoor enthusiast|outdoorsman]]. Dr. James MacCallum contributed stories to this image.{{sfnb|Silcox|Town|2017|p=236}} He has often been remembered as an expert [[wikt:canoeist|canoeist]], though David Silcox has argued that this image is romanticized.{{sfnb|Silcox|Town|2017|p=237}} In the case of fishing however, he was no doubt proficient. He had a deep love of fishing for his entire life, so much so that his reputation through Algonquin Park was equally divided between art and [[angling]].{{sfnb|Hunter|2002|p=28}} While most who visited the Park were led by hired guides, he moved through on his own. Indeed, many of his fishing locations appear in his work.{{sfnb|Hunter|2002|p=29}}

